definition.value: A member of the class of  7-hydroxyisoflavones which consists of isoflavone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 5, 7, 3' and 4'. It has been isolated from the mycelia of Cordyceps sinensis.

A glycosyloxyflavone that consists of myricetin attached to a alpha-L-rhamnopyranosyl residue at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage. Isolated from Myrica cerifera, it exhibits anti-allergic activity.
A gallate ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of gallic acid with the (3R)-hydroxy group of epicatechin. A natural product found in Parapiptadenia rigida.
Further classification will be integrated for this class
An N-acylglycine that is hippuric acid (N-benzoylglycine) substituted at position 3 on the phenyl ring by a hydroxy group.
A beta-diketone that is methane in which two of the hydrogens are substituted by 4-hydroxycinnamoyl groups.
An aryl sulfate that is quinol (hydroquinone) with one of the two hydroxy groups substituted by a sulfo group.
A type of tannin usually found in brown algae such as kelps and rockweeds. Unlike the hydrolysable or condensed tannins, these compounds are oligomers of phloroglucinol.
A a gallocatechin that has (2S,3R)-configuration.
Any ketone that is 1,3-diphenylpropanone and its derivatives obtained by substitution.
A homopolysaccharide derivative which is formally derived from a glucan.

Members of the class of tetrahydrochromenochromene that consists of a cis-fused tetrahydrochromeno[3,4-b]chromene skeleton and its substituted derivatives. The term was originally restricted to natural products, but is now also used to describe semi-synthetic and fully synthetic compounds.

A type-A lantibiotic containing 34 amino acid residues (including lanthionine (Lan), methyllanthionine (MeLan), didehydroalanine (Dha) and didehydroaminobutyric acid (Dhb)) and five thioether bridges. It is obtained by fermentation of the bacterium Lactococcus lactis and shows particular activity against Clostridium botulinum. It is used in the production of various processed foods to suppress Gram-positive spoilage and pathogenic bacteria and so extend shelf life.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): preservative.

A class of peptide antibiotic characterised by the presence of the rare thioether amino acids lanthionine or methyllanthionine, as well as the unsaturated amino acids dehydroalanine and 2-aminoisobutyric acid. In contrast to classical peptide antibiotics, lantibiotics are synthesised from precursor genes using the ribosomal pathway and the characteristic rare amino acids are introduced by posttranslational modification procedues into the lantibiotic precursor peptides ('prepeptides'). Lantibiotics are subdivided into two types: type A have long, flexible structures, while type B have rigid, globular structures.
Any lantibiotic which has which has a long, flexible structure.
Any 1-benzopyran with an aryl substituent at position 4. The term was originally restricted to natural products, but is now also used to describe semi-synthetic and fully synthetic compounds.
A member of the class of flavans in which one or more ring hydrogens are replaced by hydroxy groups.

Any organic molecular entity whose stucture is based on derivatives of a phenyl-substituted 1-phenylpropane possessing a C15 or C16 skeleton, or such a structure which is condensed with a C6-C3 lignan precursors. The term is a 'superclass' comprising all members of the classes of flavonoid, isoflavonoid, neoflavonoid, chalcones, dihydrochalcones, aurones, pterocarpan, coumestans, rotenoid, flavonolignan, homoflavonoid and flavonoid oligomers. Originally restricted to natural products, the term is also applied to synthetic compounds related to them.
Any isoflavonoid with a 3,4-dihydro-3-aryl-2H-1-benzopyran skeleton and its substituted derivatives.
Members of the class of benzofurochromene with a 6H-[1]benzofuro[3,2-c]chromene skeleton and its substituted derivatives. They are the 3,4-didehydroderivatives of pterocarpans.
A member of the class of coumestans that is 6H-[1]benzofuro[3,2-c]chromene substituted by an oxo group at position 6.
A cyclic ketal in which the ketal carbon is the only common atom of two rings.
Any molecule that consists of at least one carbon atom as part of the electrically neutral entity.
An HETE having a 9-hydroxy group and (5E)-, (7Z)-, (11Z)- and (14Z)-double bonds.
A biomacromolecule composed of carbohydrate residues which is secreted by a microorganism into the surrounding environment.
A 20-carbon, polyunsaturated fatty acid having two double bonds at unspecified positions.
The simplest member of the class of pterocarpans that is 6a,11a-dihydro-6H-[1]benzofuro[3,2-c]chromene.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid that contains three double bonds.
An isothiocyanate with the formula CH2=CHCH2N=C=S. A colorless oil with boiling point 152degreeC, it is responsible for the pungent taste of mustard, horseradish, and wasabi.

A vitamin D that is calciol or its hydroxylated metabolites calcidiol and calcitriol. Calciol (also known as vitamin D3) acts as a hormone precursor, being hydroxylated in the liver to calcidiol (25-hydroxyvitamin D3), which is then further hydroxylated in the kidney to give calcitriol (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3), the active hormone.
An organic anion that is the conjugate base of genistein, obtained by selective deprotonation of the 7-hydroxy group.
A member of the class of isoflavones having one or more glycosyl residues attached at unspecified positions.
Any inorganic sulfate salt resulting from the formal condensation of aluminium hydroxide with 1.5 mol eq. of sulfuric acid.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): firming agent.
An anthocyanin cation that is the 3-O-beta-D-glucoside of peonidin (methylcyanidin).
An anthocyanidin 3-O-beta-D-sambubioside having cyanidin as the anthocyanidin component.

A macrolide antibiotic that has formula C33H47NO13, produced by several Streptomyces species including Streptomyces natalensis. It exhibits broad spectrum antifungal activity and used in eye drops, and as a food preservative, and also as a postharvest biofungicide for citrus and other fruit crops.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): preservative.
A hydroxyisoflavone that is daidzein bearing an additional hydroxy substituent at position 6.
A trihydroxyflavanone that consists of 3'-methoxyflavanone in which the three hydroxy substituents are located at positions 4', 5, and 7.
Any oligosaccharide that has a biosynthetic pathway in common with that of raffinose.
A flavanone glycoside that is  eriodictyol substituted by a 2-O-(6-deoxy-alpha-L-mannopyranosyl)-beta-D-glucopyranosyl residue at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
An anthocyanidin chloride that has peonidin as the cationic component.
A dihydroxyflavone in which the two hydroxy groups are located at positions 5 and 7.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid containing 22 carbons and 2 double bonds
An organic sodium salt having lactate as the counterion.
LanguaL term definition: Food additive; technological purpose(s): acidity regulator, antioxidant synergist, bodying agent, bulking agent, humectant.
